    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If both parties are fighting over the outcome, the situation moves from a simple escrow function to a legal dispute, and this is where the escrow agent's role becomes very limited. They are not judges; they are custodians of the funds, acting strictly on the written contract. If the contract is silent or ambiguous on who is right, the money can indeed get stuck in limbo until a decision is reached.\n\nWhen a dispute arises, the escrow agent will usually advise both parties to seek mediation or legal counsel. They will hold the funds in escrow, refusing to release them until a formal resolution is presented, such as a signed mutual release or a court order. This prevents either side from unilaterally taking the money.\n\nIn the worst-case scenario, if the seller tries to claim the money unfairly, the escrow agent's neutrality is their shield, but ultimately, a judge or arbitrator will have to rule on whether the contract was breached and who is entitled to the funds. It’s a serious escalation, which is why getting everything crystal clear in the contract upfront is paramount.\n\nIt's a high-stakes situation, and it's why you need a real estate attorney involved if the negotiations sour past the point of simple disagreement. You",
